247
00:14:53.728 --> 00:14:57.428
If they were undergoing surgery, we also took an extra sample, and then if they are

248
00:14:57.448 --> 00:15:00.958
going through radiation or chemoradiation, we have two time points,

249
00:15:01.428 --> 00:15:05.348
mainly because we didn't really know what was the correct time point, which is the

250
00:15:05.448 --> 00:15:09.388
best time point. So we wanted to collect one that is fairly early on at four

251
00:15:09.448 --> 00:15:12.968
to six weeks after the treatment is finished.

252
00:15:13.808 --> 00:15:17.108
And we wanted to also collect one at around eight to 12 weeks.

253
00:15:17.448 --> 00:15:21.108
And if that one is in the follow-up point time two is equivocal,

254
00:15:21.388 --> 00:15:23.988
we would draw another one at week 14 to

255
00:15:24.348 --> 00:15:28.328
16 as follow-up time point three. If they're MRD

256
00:15:28.368 --> 00:15:32.128
positive in this particular study, we again stayed on

257
00:15:32.188 --> 00:15:35.968
with the NeoGenomics assay as well as the HPV sequencing,

258
00:15:36.688 --> 00:15:40.288
and we would randomize them to a

259
00:15:40.468 --> 00:15:44.048
bispecific. This is a study in collaboration with AstraZeneca,

260
00:15:44.468 --> 00:15:47.268
where we had access to the PD-1

261
00:15:48.268 --> 00:15:52.188
T-digit bispecific revagostamic, which is undergoing

262
00:15:52.468 --> 00:15:56.428
investigational trials in lung cancer as well as other cancers.

263
00:15:56.748 --> 00:16:00.108
Patients were randomized to that or in

264
00:16:00.168 --> 00:16:02.228
observation, and the ratio was

265
00:16:03.208 --> 00:16:06.508
meant to be three to one, so three to active drug versus one to

266
00:16:06.608 --> 00:16:10.508
observation. Which is the standard of care because we normally would not be testing

267
00:16:10.548 --> 00:16:14.308
these patients with any further drugs because we wouldn't know that they have MRD.

268
00:16:14.728 --> 00:16:18.648
And then the primary endpoint for this study would be clearance of their

269
00:16:18.728 --> 00:16:22.448
ctDNA in part D, which is the follow-up time point at week

270
00:16:22.548 --> 00:16:26.088
two and week 10 post-completion of their treatment.

271
00:16:26.468 --> 00:16:30.438
And those who are MRD negative by the assay, we would continue to follow them and

272
00:16:30.448 --> 00:16:34.288
see how they fare. So that was our original plan

273
00:16:34.368 --> 00:16:36.628
with a goal to enroll 200 patients.

274
00:16:38.208 --> 00:16:41.328
We did not do that because I'll tell you later in the story, we

275
00:16:42.008 --> 00:16:45.998
finished at around 50 patients, of which I'll give you some results, some hint of

276
00:16:46.028 --> 00:16:49.888
the results. The patients that we included in the MERIDIAN assay, just in a

277
00:16:49.967 --> 00:16:53.108
very brief summary, are patients with head neck cancer.

278
00:16:53.518 --> 00:16:57.058
The key primary sites, which are oral cavity, oropharynx,

279
00:16:57.268 --> 00:17:01.168
larynx, hypopharynx, and known primary, and patients that

280
00:17:01.188 --> 00:17:04.969
are high risk HPV positive, or in general, most

281
00:17:05.008 --> 00:17:08.668
HPV negative patients are high risk, so stage three and stage four

282
00:17:09.128 --> 00:17:12.618
HPV negative patients undergoing curative treatment,

283
00:17:13.028 --> 00:17:17.008
and they should have no contraindication for immunotherapy and have good organ

284
00:17:17.028 --> 00:17:20.808
functions because they could be randomized to receive the bispecific.

285
00:17:21.537 --> 00:17:25.328
And the interception part for them to enter

286
00:17:25.368 --> 00:17:29.028
that part, they have to have a positive ctDNA result

287
00:17:29.068 --> 00:17:32.288
because we need MRD patients at either follow-up point two

288
00:17:32.948 --> 00:17:36.408
or follow-up point three if it's needed to confirm that if

289
00:17:36.628 --> 00:17:38.688
follow-up point two was equivocal.

290
00:17:39.948 --> 00:17:43.128
They have to have PD-L1 expression because they're going on to an

291
00:17:43.168 --> 00:17:46.338
immunotherapy, and as I mentioned, to have no evidence of

292
00:17:46.408 --> 00:17:49.288
macroscopic recurrence or disease.

293
00:17:51.188 --> 00:17:55.128
So the assay that we needed real-time return was the point

294
00:17:55.168 --> 00:17:59.088
that we needed to determine MRD, so the part B follow-up time

295
00:17:59.168 --> 00:18:02.648
point, and then we also wanted the treatment time point to be

296
00:18:02.748 --> 00:18:06.728
real-time return. All the other time points for both assays

297
00:18:06.808 --> 00:18:10.728
were banked for later analyses. So obviously, we will

298
00:18:10.768 --> 00:18:14.588
be presenting on the RADAR results during this meeting.

299
00:18:14.888 --> 00:18:18.368
The HPV assay will be presented at a later time point.

300
00:18:20.028 --> 00:18:23.828
As I mentioned, we wanted to enroll 200 patients, and we were ambitious.

301
00:18:23.868 --> 00:18:27.708
We were able to enroll the first 50 patients, and we

302
00:18:27.748 --> 00:18:30.047
decided to take a look at that point.

303
00:18:30.568 --> 00:18:34.448
Out of the 50 or so patients, about 42 were evaluable at

304
00:18:34.488 --> 00:18:38.308
time point two, and out of that, five of them had

305
00:18:38.468 --> 00:18:42.212
positive ctDNA. But as you can seeOut of those

306
00:18:42.232 --> 00:18:46.092
patients, many of them actually have macroscopic disease at

307
00:18:46.132 --> 00:18:48.912
the time of us finding the positive ctDNA.

308
00:18:49.272 --> 00:18:52.852
So at the end, we're only able to enroll two patients, one

309
00:18:52.892 --> 00:18:55.912
randomized to active treatment and one did not.

310
00:18:56.612 --> 00:19:00.232
And we'll tell you later on that one patient who

311
00:19:00.272 --> 00:19:04.192
received the active treatment with the bispecific is free of recurrence

312
00:19:04.252 --> 00:19:07.592
for over 22 months, and the person that was randomized to

313
00:19:07.632 --> 00:19:10.912
observation, unfortunately, had disease progression.

314
00:19:10.972 --> 00:19:14.692
There was a couple of patients with equivocal ctDNA at

315
00:19:15.012 --> 00:19:18.572
follow-up point two, so we had to do the follow-up point three,

316
00:19:18.912 --> 00:19:20.872
and one was positive and one was negative.

317
00:19:20.982 --> 00:19:24.772
The positive patient was moved into that MRD positive

318
00:19:24.872 --> 00:19:28.732
arm. In those who are negative for ctDNA so far, out of

319
00:19:28.772 --> 00:19:32.672
the 35 patients, 30 are alive without recurrence, one

320
00:19:32.732 --> 00:19:36.382
is alive with recurrence, one is diseased with recurrence,

321
00:19:36.772 --> 00:19:39.412
and one is diseased without recurrence.

322
00:19:39.452 --> 00:19:43.052
So at the end of part B, which is our

323
00:19:43.132 --> 00:19:46.442
MRD window, about six patients were

324
00:19:46.492 --> 00:19:50.022
ctDNA positive, but as I mentioned, some of them did have

325
00:19:50.052 --> 00:19:52.612
positive clinical recurrence at that time.

326
00:19:52.952 --> 00:19:56.532
So another take-home point is that MRD is not MRD

327
00:19:56.572 --> 00:20:00.182
unless you really confirm that they do not have clinical radiological

328
00:20:00.212 --> 00:20:04.032
recurrence. So this is the patient that was randomized to active treatment.

329
00:20:05.012 --> 00:20:05.432
He was

330
00:20:06.312 --> 00:20:10.132
treated with rivogostumab, and he has now been disease-free for

331
00:20:10.372 --> 00:20:11.152
22 months.

332
00:20:12.732 --> 00:20:14.612
And these are the Kaplan-Meier curves.

333
00:20:14.672 --> 00:20:18.232
What we have learned that as you use more follow-up time

334
00:20:18.272 --> 00:20:22.212
points instead of just landmark time points, or as you follow them

335
00:20:22.272 --> 00:20:25.292
in any follow-up time points, the sensitivity increases.

336
00:20:25.332 --> 00:20:29.232
And I think that's fairly true for most cancers, that a surveillance

337
00:20:29.852 --> 00:20:33.492
strategy would give you more chance of

338
00:20:33.572 --> 00:20:37.552
catching the MRD than to have very specific time points,

339
00:20:37.792 --> 00:20:39.272
so-called landmark testing.

340
00:20:40.112 --> 00:20:43.782
And again, I urge you to go to Dr. Sand's presentation

341
00:20:43.812 --> 00:20:47.112
tomorrow where he'll present everything in a much greater

342
00:20:47.152 --> 00:20:50.562
detail. But as expected, those who are MRD positive have

343
00:20:50.951 --> 00:20:54.812
a much poorer relapse-free survival, and those who are MRD negative

344
00:20:54.892 --> 00:20:58.792
had a much better relapse-free survival with a hazard ratio that

345
00:20:58.872 --> 00:20:59.792
is significant.

346
00:21:00.972 --> 00:21:04.812
So you will ask, so what's going on in the literature in that area?

347
00:21:04.912 --> 00:21:08.752
So I've summarized the current literature to date with the orange

348
00:21:08.912 --> 00:21:12.472
part being assays that are tumor-informed, as I

349
00:21:12.532 --> 00:21:16.461
mentioned, that you needed to sequence a tumor and then subsequently

350
00:21:16.512 --> 00:21:20.432
look into the plasma, and the bottom part being tumor agnostic, which

351
00:21:20.472 --> 00:21:22.492
you do not need to have access to the tumor.

352
00:21:22.872 --> 00:21:24.032
You use the assay

353
00:21:25.052 --> 00:21:28.092
on the plasma by itself. So in

354
00:21:29.552 --> 00:21:33.372
cases like these cases, these presentations, or these publications, you

355
00:21:33.412 --> 00:21:37.052
can see that the tumor-informed assays generally have a higher

356
00:21:37.612 --> 00:21:40.892
baseline detection, which is not surprising because you know what you're looking

357
00:21:40.901 --> 00:21:42.612
for and you have a more sensitive assay.

358
00:21:42.882 --> 00:21:46.392
And the tumor-agnostic assays tend to have a slightly

359
00:21:46.452 --> 00:21:48.372
lower baseline detection.

360
00:21:49.192 --> 00:21:51.572
You can also see in the parts where you have serial

361
00:21:52.472 --> 00:21:56.241
collection has a better sensitivity and limit of detection,

362
00:21:56.892 --> 00:22:00.172
or better sensitivity versus a single time point where the

363
00:22:00.192 --> 00:22:03.632
sensitivity is by and large lower.

364
00:22:03.712 --> 00:22:07.681
All of them have a lead time of approximately 4 to 10 months, and

365
00:22:07.712 --> 00:22:11.432
when they're able to detect a ctDNA in the plasma, the hazard

366
00:22:11.472 --> 00:22:15.372
ratio for relapse or survival is much worse than those who are MRD

367
00:22:15.432 --> 00:22:17.792
negative. So that's the current literature.

368
00:22:17.852 --> 00:22:21.612
This field is definitely evolving, and I think you should

369
00:22:21.622 --> 00:22:25.212
definitely keep an eye on this space, and certainly, I think our

370
00:22:25.232 --> 00:22:29.002
take-home from Meridian is that we need to find an assay that is

371
00:22:29.012 --> 00:22:32.752
continuing to be more sensitive to be able to detect very,

372
00:22:32.852 --> 00:22:36.332
very low quantities of ctDNA, and that longitudinal

373
00:22:36.452 --> 00:22:39.572
tracking may further expand your interception

374
00:22:39.692 --> 00:22:43.282
opportunities. I think HPV testing is also another

375
00:22:43.332 --> 00:22:47.212
opportunity for MRD detection in this viral-driven cancer, and it

376
00:22:47.252 --> 00:22:51.052
will definitely complement mutation-based testing in those who are

377
00:22:51.312 --> 00:22:54.312
having HPV-positive oropharyngeal cancers.

378
00:22:54.772 --> 00:22:58.672
So what are we doing in Meridian? We have amended the protocol.

379
00:22:58.772 --> 00:23:02.172
We have adopted a newer assay, a more

380
00:23:02.212 --> 00:23:05.632
ultrasensitive assay, and we have just reopened

381
00:23:06.372 --> 00:23:10.152
for the next 50 patients to see whether by having

382
00:23:10.232 --> 00:23:13.512
a different assay, we can have a higher chance of

383
00:23:13.552 --> 00:23:17.372
detecting MRD. Because clearly, we have seen the hint

384
00:23:17.432 --> 00:23:21.072
that that one patient we're able to randomize to the active

385
00:23:21.082 --> 00:23:24.172
treatment, we are able to intercept this disease.

386
00:23:24.212 --> 00:23:27.892
So I think if we're able to catch more of these cancers, we

387
00:23:27.912 --> 00:23:31.692
are possibly able to change the outcome of these patients.

388
00:23:34.292 --> 00:23:37.212
Just some words about MRD and cancer interception.

389
00:23:37.312 --> 00:23:39.012
Perhaps the poster child for this

390
00:23:40.312 --> 00:23:43.932
strategy is in bladder cancer. As many of you are aware of IMvigor

391
00:23:44.012 --> 00:23:47.752
11 that was published in "The New England Journal of Medicine" by Tom Powles

392
00:23:47.812 --> 00:23:50.192
last year, where patients who have

393
00:23:50.912 --> 00:23:54.552
post-surgery for their bladder cancer, who have MRD

394
00:23:54.592 --> 00:23:58.552
positive by ctDNA and receive immunotherapy did

395
00:23:58.652 --> 00:24:01.652
much better in terms of PFS and OS,

396
00:24:01.752 --> 00:24:05.632
DFS and OS than those who are MRD negative

397
00:24:05.672 --> 00:24:09.592
with negative ctDNA. So there is definitely proof of concept out there

398
00:24:09.632 --> 00:24:13.472
with certain diseases, but clearly one size cannot fit all.

399
00:24:13.512 --> 00:24:17.402
We cannot say it works for every cancer, and the

400
00:24:17.472 --> 00:24:19.992
challenges of different cancers are different.

401
00:24:20.032 --> 00:24:24.012
Colon cancer perhaps is a bit easier, for example, to detect MRD than

402
00:24:24.072 --> 00:24:26.352
head and neck cancer than some of the other cancers.

403
00:24:26.412 --> 00:24:29.312
So the context is really important for

404
00:24:29.512 --> 00:24:30.972
pan-tumor targeting.

405
00:24:32.192 --> 00:24:35.532
So a few words about what we're doing in our institution about MRD.

406
00:24:35.672 --> 00:24:39.192
We were very fortunate in the last several months receive a

407
00:24:39.212 --> 00:24:42.432
donation from a philanthropist, Mr.

408
00:24:42.672 --> 00:24:46.452
Peter Gillgan, who donated 50 millions to us for

409
00:24:47.112 --> 00:24:49.372
understanding early cancer detection.

410
00:24:49.412 --> 00:24:53.092
Thanks for clapping, Eddie .And we

411
00:24:53.472 --> 00:24:57.112
are excited and we show them our vision that we

412
00:24:57.172 --> 00:25:00.802
wanted to catch cancers early. We spend a lot of our energy on

413
00:25:00.852 --> 00:25:04.792
advanced cancers, and it's important to do that, but it's even

414
00:25:04.852 --> 00:25:08.192
more important to catch these cancers early.

415
00:25:08.252 --> 00:25:12.172
So we explained the whole concept to Mr.

416
00:25:12.272 --> 00:25:16.092
Gilgan, and he think this is a good way to invest his donation.

417
00:25:16.652 --> 00:25:20.532
So we decided to create hopefully the world's largest MRD cohort,

418
00:25:20.572 --> 00:25:24.132
and this is a pan-cancer cohort. Our goal is ambitious.

419
00:25:24.252 --> 00:25:27.192
We wanted to enroll 7,000 patients over four years.

420
00:25:27.252 --> 00:25:31.161
We put our first patient in on March 31st, and

421
00:25:31.212 --> 00:25:35.072
this is for all cancers. We're actively working on

422
00:25:35.112 --> 00:25:37.672
getting engagement from all our disease sites.

423
00:25:38.032 --> 00:25:38.452
I think if

424
00:25:39.332 --> 00:25:43.192
anything is successful, engagement of the multidisciplinary groups in our

425
00:25:43.252 --> 00:25:47.112
institution is going to be one of the most important

426
00:25:47.552 --> 00:25:51.372
first endpoints. We'll be collecting serial time points, as I

427
00:25:51.412 --> 00:25:55.232
mentioned. I think single time point is probably not as good as serial time points.

428
00:25:55.731 --> 00:25:59.692
And we're going to learn a lot in terms of multimodal testing,

429
00:25:59.752 --> 00:26:03.252
not just ctDNA, but also radiomics, machine learning, et cetera.

430
00:26:03.672 --> 00:26:06.052
And we're actively also planning interception.

431
00:26:06.332 --> 00:26:10.272
Not just escalation when they're MRD positive, but also de-escalation if

432
00:26:10.312 --> 00:26:14.212
they're MRD negative. So we have actually planned a whole journey

433
00:26:14.232 --> 00:26:17.622
for these patients. We've created the infrastructure to do this with

434
00:26:18.272 --> 00:26:21.702
nurse navigators. Patients are going to receive electronic

435
00:26:21.712 --> 00:26:24.672
consenting. They will really understand what

436
00:26:25.392 --> 00:26:28.762
MRD means, and we will track them both MRD negative and

437
00:26:28.792 --> 00:26:29.412
positive.

438
00:26:30.872 --> 00:26:32.672
And as I mentioned, we are actively planning

439
00:26:33.732 --> 00:26:37.452
interception study to prove the utility of MRD interception,

440
00:26:37.772 --> 00:26:41.712
because it's important, obviously, to escalate if they're positive, but if they're

441
00:26:41.772 --> 00:26:45.732
negative, maybe we can think about opportunities to give them less toxic treatment

442
00:26:45.772 --> 00:26:49.332
or shorter treatments so that they don't have to actually go through

443
00:26:49.372 --> 00:26:52.672
toxic treatments without compromising cure.

444
00:26:52.852 --> 00:26:56.672
So that's an important consideration for pan-cancer,

445
00:26:57.032 --> 00:26:58.872
pan-tumor MRD interception.

446
00:27:00.411 --> 00:27:04.032
I'm going to switch gear now to advanced cancers, just to

447
00:27:04.212 --> 00:27:08.132
give a first story where we have, many years ago,

448
00:27:08.252 --> 00:27:10.572
created a platform study called INSPIRE.

449
00:27:11.472 --> 00:27:14.112
The name is really trying to inspire our

450
00:27:15.032 --> 00:27:18.052
surgeons, our scientists, as well as

451
00:27:18.592 --> 00:27:20.992
oncologists to work together on immunotherapy.

452
00:27:21.412 --> 00:27:25.252
So we put 100 patients on immunotherapy with pembrolizumab,

453
00:27:25.752 --> 00:27:29.552
and we collected all kinds of samples from these patients, tumor,

454
00:27:29.732 --> 00:27:33.082
blood, et cetera. And over the course of two years,

455
00:27:33.152 --> 00:27:36.732
2016 and 2018, we collected close to 200

456
00:27:36.912 --> 00:27:39.812
biopsies and over 2,500 blood samples.

457
00:27:40.292 --> 00:27:43.981
This study has been well-published, and you can see we have

458
00:27:44.132 --> 00:27:47.972
many, many papers. But I think the biggest reward of this

459
00:27:48.072 --> 00:27:51.672
study is, number one, we built a team that is

460
00:27:51.732 --> 00:27:55.512
extremely interactive. We meet regularly with these

461
00:27:55.612 --> 00:27:59.532
kinds of projects now. There's engagement, there's interest from clinicians

462
00:27:59.552 --> 00:28:01.772
to hear about the scientists' work and vice versa.

463
00:28:02.452 --> 00:28:06.232
And I want to point out in red, these are young investigators in our

464
00:28:06.272 --> 00:28:10.052
institution. They are the first authors of these papers, many of which are high

465
00:28:10.112 --> 00:28:12.022
impact journals with high

466
00:28:13.052 --> 00:28:16.752
impact factors and readership. We wanted to promote our young

467
00:28:16.812 --> 00:28:20.652
investigators to be in charge and to lead, and I think this is a

468
00:28:20.712 --> 00:28:24.052
great way to do so. So we

469
00:28:24.692 --> 00:28:28.571
have many readouts from INSPIRE, which I do not have time to really highlight.

470
00:28:29.132 --> 00:28:32.832
One of the thing that we did is we did do a tumor-informed assay using the

471
00:28:32.852 --> 00:28:36.772
biomarker collection for the ctDNA and actually

472
00:28:36.832 --> 00:28:40.492
helped with the ctDNA monitoring for immunotherapy with the

473
00:28:40.512 --> 00:28:43.672
Signatera assay. So you will see that it was

474
00:28:43.912 --> 00:28:47.672
referenced in the Signatera in terms of the INSPIRE

475
00:28:47.732 --> 00:28:48.192
study.

476
00:28:49.812 --> 00:28:53.252
I'm going to highlight some work that we did again with Enrique, who is in the

477
00:28:53.292 --> 00:28:55.832
audience. We were also curious about

478
00:28:57.292 --> 00:28:58.332
if you collect

479
00:28:59.452 --> 00:29:03.032
very frequent blood samples in patients with advanced cancers on

480
00:29:03.072 --> 00:29:06.812
immunotherapy, when is the time that is the most sensitive

481
00:29:06.852 --> 00:29:10.392
time point? So again, we collected many, many time points,

482
00:29:10.652 --> 00:29:14.352
literally eight time points after the first dose of immunotherapy.

483
00:29:14.382 --> 00:29:18.322
This was all PD-1 antibody-treated patients,

484
00:29:18.412 --> 00:29:18.632
either

485
00:29:19.532 --> 00:29:23.072
pembrolizumab or nivolumab. And the times were at day

486
00:29:23.192 --> 00:29:27.032
zero, day two, day three, day eight, day 15, 22,

487
00:29:27.132 --> 00:29:30.652
and 29. You can see that it's a very intensive

